            <Title>Goals</Title>
            <Text>More character-driven.
One of the big 'challenges' I want to get into is developing exciting, humorous, *believable* NPCs in Inform7 -- a task that is near and dear to Emily Short's own research efforts.  This is a real challenge and there's a lot of prior work to study and build on.   Character relationships should be at the heart of the story.

Conversational Focus
In writing the sequel I'd like to make a very conscious effort to be efficient in terms of writing time -- this is more of an issue this year since I won't have a long, European vacation all summer in 2010. The writing for RDO was broad and deep -- there's stuff in there that no one will ever hit, but I enjoyed putting it in for that 1/100 person that will randomly try to surrender in French, attempt to sudo the ACU, etc. While I enjoy these Easter Eggs, I'd like to focus on game elements that are likely to be seen, and to smoothly highlight those elements so that the amount of time spent working on a section is mirrored by player exposure those sections. Every object will still have strong depth of description, but overall, I'd like to pick our battles more selectively. If we chose one item to focus our firepower on in this game, I'd like it to be conversation. It's an IF holy grail, and something that not many people can do well. There's also room for innovation (see section "conversation").

Less hard sci-fi, more ethical/moral tensions
Emily Short believes that good sci-fi is mainly about the question of what it means to be human, and/or ethical/moral;  the science merely provides the interesting scenario in which to examine these issues.

Strong upfront player engagement

Episode should stand alone, as well as work as sequel

Some analogue of the remember verb

"Building sense of urgency" â€” which Emily liked so much.   
Probably comes from years of Nascrag end-of-round-2-death-trap scenarios.  But a bit of nail-biting (like the boarding scene) is good once per adventure.  :-)  A golden banana of discord.  Literally.  -Ben Collins-Sussman 10/14/09 11:35 AMHah! -john welch 10/15/09 11:11 PM 

Some of the props from RDO should appear 
-- e.g., Janet's oversize blue futon should end up in her bedroom on the ship.


NON-GOALS â€” AVOID THESE!
Waking up with a hangover, in a cave, speaking only German.
Boredom and repetition.
Anything that will lose the fickle faith of the judges/players in the first ten minutes.
Obvious technomasturbation Ã  la this year's unix command line, man pages, etc.
Multiple character perspectives.
</Text>
